# Authentication & Authorization

## Never Trust from Frontend

Never trust `userId`, `departmentId`, or `role` from request body, query params, or client headers.

Always derive identity and permissions server-side:

```
Session → Policy → Application Service
```

## Rules

- Identity comes from the authenticated session (JWT, cookie, or session store) — not from the client payload.
- Authorization checks happen in middleware/guards or service layer before business logic runs.
- Department Head (and similar scoped roles) must always verify `departmentId` against the session user's department.
- Policies encode "can this user do this action on this resource?" — keep them explicit and testable.

## Examples

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — trusts client-supplied userId
async updateProfile(req) {
  return userRepo.update(req.body.userId, req.body);
}

// ✅ GOOD — uses session identity
async updateProfile(req) {
  const userId = req.session.userId;
  return userRepo.update(userId, req.body);
}
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — Department Head can access any department
if (user.role === 'department_head') { /* allow */ }

// ✅ GOOD — scoped to user's department
if (user.role === 'department_head' && resource.departmentId === user.departmentId) { /* allow */ }
```
